55. formidolosis, ‘awe-inspiring' 3 ef. Virg. G. 4. 467 et caliyantem niqra formidine lucum. Many Mss. give formidolosae, but the balance of the sentence makes it probable that silvis has an adj. like ferae and sopore. For a truer picture of beasts of prey at night cf. Ps. civ. 20-22. 57. ‘ May the hounds of the Subura bark, so that (lit. ‘a thing at which ') all may laugh, at the adulterous old man besmeared with unguents such that my hands never compounded any more perfect.' The Subura was a street of bad repute running through the valley between the Esquiline, Quirinal and Viminal. Canidia imagines old Varus hurrying to her house in it so perfumed that all the dogs sniff and bark at him. The ‘unguent ’ is probably one she has sent him, and is supposed to exercise a charm over him, cf. line 69.
